TY  - JOUR
T1  - Managing from the Boundary: The Effective Leadership of Self-Managing Work Teams
AU  - Druskat, Vanessa Urch
AU  - Wheeler, Jane V.
Y1  - 2003/08/01
PY  - 2003
DA  - 2003/08/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/30040637
DO  - 10.5465/30040637
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 435
EP  - 457
VL  - 46
IS  - 4
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - We used in-depth critical incident interviews with the external leaders of self-managing work teams and their team members, and interviews and surveys provided by managers, to understand how effective leader behaviors and strategies unfold over time. Content analyses of the data produced a process model showing that effective external leaders move back and forth across boundaries to build relationships, scout necessary information, persuade their teams and outside constituents to support one another, and empower their teams to achieve success.
AB  - We used in-depth critical incident interviews with the external leaders of self-managing work teams and their team members, and interviews and surveys provided by managers, to understand how effective leader behaviors and strategies unfold over time. Content analyses of the data produced a process model showing that effective external leaders move back and forth across boundaries to build relationships, scout necessary information, persuade their teams and outside constituents to support one another, and empower their teams to achieve success.
