TY  - JOUR
T1  - Happy Together? How Using Nonstandard Workers Affects Exit, Voice, and Loyalty Among Standard Employees
AU  - Davis-Blake, Alison
AU  - Broschak, Joseph P.
AU  - George, Elizabeth
Y1  - 2003/08/01
PY  - 2003
DA  - 2003/08/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/30040639
DO  - 10.5465/30040639
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 475
EP  - 485
VL  - 46
IS  - 4
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - We examined how a blended workforce (one with ?standard? and ?nonstandard? workers in the same jobs) affected exit, ?voice,? and loyalty among standard employees. We found that workforce blending worsened relations between managers and employees, decreased standard employees' loyalty, and increased their interest both in leaving their organizations and in exercising voice through unionization. However, these effects were contingent on whether the nonstandard workers were temporary or contract and on the salary and responsibilities of the standard employees.
AB  - We examined how a blended workforce (one with ?standard? and ?nonstandard? workers in the same jobs) affected exit, ?voice,? and loyalty among standard employees. We found that workforce blending worsened relations between managers and employees, decreased standard employees' loyalty, and increased their interest both in leaving their organizations and in exercising voice through unionization. However, these effects were contingent on whether the nonstandard workers were temporary or contract and on the salary and responsibilities of the standard employees.
